# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: strikeout
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:strikeout/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The **1903 World Series** was the first modern World Series to be played in Major League Baseball.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] It matched the American League (AL) champion Boston Americans (now the Boston Red Sox) against the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates in a best-of-nine series, with Boston prevailing five games to three, winning the last four.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] This was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Boston-based team.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The first three games were played in Boston, the next four in Allegheny (home of the Pirates), and the eighth (last) game in Boston.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Pittsburgh pitcher Sam Leever injured his shoulder while trap shooting, so his teammate Deacon Phillippe pitched five complete games.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Phillippe won three of his games, but it was not enough to overcome the club from the new American League.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Boston pitchers Bill Dinneen and Cy Young led Boston to victory.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] In Game 1, Phillippe struck out ten Boston batters.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The next day, Dinneen bettered that mark, striking out 11 Pittsburgh batters in Game 2.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Honus Wagner, bothered by injuries, batted only 6-for-27 (.222) in the Series and committed six errors.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The shortstop was deeply distraught by his performance.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The following spring, Wagner (who in 1903 led the National League in batting average) refused to send his portrait to a "Hall of Fame" for batting champions.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] "I was a joke in that Boston-Pittsburgh Series.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] What does it profit a man to hammer along and make a few hits when they are not needed only to fall down when it comes to a pinch?
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Due to overflow crowds at the Exposition Park games in Allegheny City, if a batted ball rolled under a rope in the outfield that held spectators back, a "ground-rule triple" would be scored.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] 17 ground-rule triples were hit in the four games played at the stadium.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] In the series, Boston came back from a three games to one deficit, winning the final four games to capture the title.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Such a large comeback would not happen again until the Pirates came back to defeat the Washington Senators in the 1925 World Series, and has happened only 11 times in baseball history.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] (The Pirates themselves repeated this feat in 1979 against the Baltimore Orioles.) Much was made of the influence of Boston's "Royal Rooters", who traveled to Exposition Park and sang their theme song "Tessie" to distract the opposing players (especially Wagner).
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Boston wound up winning three out of four games in Allegheny City.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Pirates owner Barney Dreyfuss added his share of the gate receipts to the players' share, so the losing team's players actually finished with a larger individual share than the winning team's.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The Series brought the new American League prestige and proved its best could beat the best of the National League, thus strengthening the demand for future World Series competitions.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] In 1901, Ban Johnson, president of the Western League, a minor league organization, formed the American League to take advantage of the National League's 1900 contraction from twelve teams to eight.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Johnson and fellow owners raided the National League and signed away many star players, including Cy Young and Jimmy Collins.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Johnson had a list of 46 National Leaguers he targeted for the American League; by 1902, all but one had made the jump.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The constant raiding, however, nixed the idea of a championship between the two leagues.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Pirates owner Barney Dreyfuss, whose team ran away with the 1902 National League pennant, was open to a postseason contest and even said he would allow the American League champion to stock its roster with all-stars.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] However, Johnson had spoken of putting a team in Pittsburgh and even attempted to raid the Pirates' roster in August 1902, which soured Dreyfuss.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] At the end of the season, however, the Pirates played a group of American League All-Stars in a four-game exhibition series, winning two games to one, with one tie.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The leagues finally called a truce in the winter of 1902–03 and formed the National Commission to preside over organized baseball.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The following season, the Boston Americans and Pittsburgh Pirates had secured their respective championship pennants by September.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] That August, Dreyfuss challenged the American League to an 11-game championship series.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Encouraged by Johnson and National League President Harry Pulliam, Americans owner Henry J.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Killilea met with Dreyfuss in Pittsburgh in September and instead agreed to a best-of-nine championship, with the first three games played in Boston, the next four in Allegheny City, and the remaining two (if necessary) in Boston.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] One significant point about this agreement was that it was an arrangement primarily between the two clubs rather than a formal arrangement between the leagues.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] In short, it was a voluntary event, a fact which would result in no Series at all for 1904.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The formal establishment of the Series as a compulsory event started in 1905.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The Pirates won their third straight pennant in 1903 thanks to a powerful lineup that included legendary shortstop Honus Wagner, who hit .355 and drove in 101 runs, player-manager Fred Clarke, who hit .351, and Ginger Beaumont, who hit .341 and led the league in hits and runs.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The Pirates' pitching was weaker than it had been in previous years but boasted 24-game winner Deacon Phillippe and 25-game winner Sam Leever.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The Americans had a strong pitching staff, led by Cy Young, who went 28–9 in 1903 and became the all-time wins leader that year.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Bill Dinneen and Long Tom Hughes, right-handers like Young, had won 21 games and 20 games each.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The Boston outfield, featuring Chick Stahl (.274), Buck Freeman (.287, 104 RBI) and Patsy Dougherty (.331, 101 runs scored) was considered excellent.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Although the Pirates had dominated their league for the previous three years, they went into the series riddled with injuries and plagued by bizarre misfortunes.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Otto Krueger, the team's only utility player, was beaned on September 19 and never fully played in the series.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] 16-game winner Ed Doheny left the team three days later, exhibiting signs of paranoia; he was committed to an insane asylum the following month.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Leever had been battling an injury to his pitching arm (which he made worse by entering a trapshooting competition).
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Worst of all, Wagner, who had a sore thumb throughout the season, injured his right leg in September and was never 100 percent for the postseason.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Some sources say Boston were heavy underdogs.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Boston bookies actually gave even odds to the teams (and only because Dreyfuss and other "sports" were alleged to have bet on Pittsburgh to bring down the odds).
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The teams were generally thought to be evenly matched, with the Americans credited with stronger pitching and the Pirates with superior offense and fielding.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The outcome, many believed, hinged on Wagner's health.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The Pirates started Game 1 strong, scoring six runs in the first four innings, and held on to win the first World Series game in modern baseball history.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] They extended their lead to 7–0 on an inside-the-park home run by Jimmy Sebring in the seventh, the first home run in World Series history.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Boston scored a few runs in the last three innings, but it was too little, too late; they ended up losing 7–3 in the first ever World Series game.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Both Phillippe and Young threw complete games, with Phillippe striking out ten and Young fanning five, but Young also gave up twice as many hits and allowed three earned runs to Phillippe's two.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] After starting out strong in Game 1, the Pirates simply shut down offensively, eking out a mere three hits, all singles.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Pittsburgh starter Sam Leever went 1 inning and gave up three hits and two runs, before his ailing arm forced him to leave in favor of Bucky Veil, who finished the game.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Bill Dinneen struck out 11 and pitched a complete game for the Americans, while Patsy Dougherty hit home runs in the first and sixth innings for two of the Boston's three runs.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The Americans' Patsy Dougherty led off the Boston scoring with an inside-the-park home run, the first time a lead-off batter did just that until Alcides Escobar of the Kansas City Royals duplicated the feat in the 2015 World Series, 112 years later.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Dougherty's second home run was the first in World Series history to actually sail over the fence, an incredibly rare feat at the time.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Phillippe, pitching after only a single day of rest, started Game 3 for the Pirates and didn't let them down, hurling his second complete-game victory of the Series to put Pittsburgh up two games to one.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] After two days of rest, Phillippe was ready to pitch a second straight game.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] He threw his third complete-game victory of the series against Bill Dinneen, who was making his second start of the series.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] But Phillippe's second straight win was almost not to be, as the Americans, down 5–1 in the top of the ninth, rallied to narrow the deficit to one run.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The comeback attempt failed, as Phillippe managed to put an end to it and give the Pirates a commanding 3–1 series lead.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Game 5 was a pitcher's duel for the first five innings, with Boston's Cy Young and Pittsburgh's Brickyard Kennedy giving up no runs.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] That changed in the top of the sixth, however, when the Americans scored a then-record six runs before being retired.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Young, on the other hand, managed to keep his shutout intact before finally giving up a pair of runs in the bottom of the eighth.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] He went the distance and struck out four for his first World Series win.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Game 6 was a rematch between the starters of Game 2, Boston's Dinneen and Pittsburgh's Leever.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Leever pitched a complete game this time but so did Dinneen, who outmatched him to earn his second complete-game victory of the series.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] After losing three of the first four games of the World Series, the underdog Americans had tied the series at three games apiece.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The fourth and final game in Allegheny saw Phillippe start his fourth game of the Series for the Pirates.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] This time, however, he did not fare as well as he did in his first three starts.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Cy Young, in his third start of the Series, held the Pirates to three runs and put the Americans ahead for the first time as the Series moved back to Boston.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The final game of this inaugural World Series started out as an intense pitcher's duel, scoreless until the bottom of the fourth when Hobe Ferris hit a two-run single.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] Phillippe started his fifth and final game of the series and Dinneen his fourth.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The Red Sox would go on to be one of the most dominant teams of the early 20th century, winning four championships in six years during the 1910s decade.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] They would start their dynasty in 1912 when they won their next championship over the New York Giants in seven games.
[src:strikeout/1903-world-series] The Pirates would return to the World Series in 1909, and defeated the Detroit Tigers in seven games to win their first championship.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The **1906 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1906 season.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The third edition of the World Series, it featured a crosstown matchup between the American League (AL) champion Chicago White Sox and the National League (NL) champion Chicago Cubs.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Cubs had posted the highest regular-season win total (116) and winning percentage (.763) in the major leagues since the advent of the modern era in 1901.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The White Sox, known as the "Hitless Wonders" after finishing with the worst team batting average (.230) in the American League, beat the Cubs in six games for one of the greatest upsets in Series history as the Sox out-pitched the Cubs in their first two wins and out-hit them in their last two.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The White Sox won their first championship in franchise history, and this was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Chicago-based team.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The home teams alternated, starting with the National League Cubs being home in Game 1.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The teams split the first four games; then the Hitless Wonders (a name coined by sportswriter Charles Dryden) exploded for 26 hits in the last two games.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] True to their nickname, the White Sox hit only .198 as a team in winning the series, but it beat the .196 average produced by the Cubs.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] In Game 3, White Sox pitcher Ed Walsh struck out 12 Cubs, breaking the previous record of 11 set by Bill Dinneen in 1903.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] National interest in the Series was strong.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Ahead of the third game, backers in Denver, Colorado offered a guarantee of US$10,000 (equivalent to $358,333 in 2025) to host the seventh game of the series should it be necessary.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Spokane (Washington) Chamber of Commerce offered US$15,000 (equivalent to $537,500 in 2025) for the game.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Series would remain in Chicago and finish in six games.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The 1906 World Series was the first to be played between two teams from the same metropolitan area or state.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] This series along with the 1944 edition (contested between the St.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Louis Browns), and the 1989 edition (contested between the San Francisco Giants and Oakland Athletics) are the only such instances outside of New York City where two teams from the same metropolitan area played in the World Series.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] This was also the last World Series where both teams were making their first appearance in the Fall Classic, something that is currently impossible without future expansion (as the Seattle Mariners are currently the only team in the league to have never appeared in a World Series).
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] White Sox starter Nick Altrock faced Cub starter Mordecai "Three-Fingered" Brown in game 1.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Both were perfect through three innings.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Cubs put a runner on second in the bottom of the fourth inning, but couldn't score.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] In the top of the fifth, George Rohe tripled to lead off, then scored on an error at home when Patsy Dougherty reached on a fielder's choice.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Sox scored a second run in the top of the sixth.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Altrock walked, and was sacrificed to second base by Ed Hahn.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Fielder Jones then singled to center but Altrock was thrown out at the plate, Jones taking second on the throw home.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] He took third on Cub catcher Johnny Kling's passed ball, and Frank Isbell drove him home with a single.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Cubs struck back in their half of the sixth.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Kling walked and Brown singled with nobody out.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] After Solly Hofman sacrificed the runners to second and third, Altrock's wild pitch scored Kling and sent Brown to third, giving him little margin for error with only one out, but he got Jimmy Sheckard to pop out and Frank Schulte to ground out to end the threat.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] He pitched beautifully for the rest of the game, allowing only one more Cub to reach second, retaining the 2–1 lead for a Game 1 Sox win.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Ed Reulbach was called on for the Cubs to face White Sox hurler Doc White.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] After matching 1–2–3 first innings, things started to fall apart for White.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] After cleanup-hitting first baseman Frank Chance led off the top of the second with a strikeout, third baseman Harry Steinfeldt singled to left field and shortstop Joe Tinker beat out a bunt.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Cubs second baseman Johnny Evers then reached on a two-base error by White Sox second baseman Frank Isbell, scoring Steinfeldt for an unearned run and moving Tinker and Evers to second and third.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Catcher Johnny Kling was then intentionally walked to load the bases and bring up the pitcher, still with only one out.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Reulbach squeeze-bunted Tinker home for a second unearned run, moving Evers to third and Kling to second with two out.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Solly Hofman followed with an infield single to shortstop Lee Tannehill, scoring Evers for a third unearned run, but when Kling tried to score from second, he was thrown out at home plate, ending the rally.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Cubs added a fourth unearned run in the third, ending Doc White's day on the mound.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Sox scored in the bottom of the fifth inning with an unearned run, thanks to a wild pitch and an error.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Cubs scored three more runs, all earned, in the sixth and eighth to win Game 2 7–1 and tie the Series at one game apiece.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Reulbach pitched the first one-hitter in World Series history.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] After allowing two first-inning hits, Sox starter "Big Ed" Walsh didn't give up another and struck out 12, giving the Sox a 2–1 edge in the series.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] After Fred Schulte's first inning two-out double, Walsh retired the next 25 of 27 Cub batters to face him.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Third baseman George Rohe cracked a two-out, bases-loaded triple to left in the top of the sixth off Jack Pfiester for the only runs of the game.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Looking to even the Series, the Cubs started Mordecai Brown on one day's rest who pitched 5+2⁄3 innings of no-hit ball for the Cubs before settling for a two-hitter.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Nick Altrock, who faced and defeated Brown in game 1, was the hard-luck loser, with the only run of the game coming on Johnny Evers' two-out single in the top of the seventh scoring Frank Chance.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Sox put the tying run on second base in the top of the ninth thanks to a two-out walk and a passed ball, but Frank Isbell grounded out to end the threat.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The game took just 96 minutes and evened the Series at two games apiece.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Game 5 was a wild affair with a total of 18 hits, ten walks, six errors, two hit batsmen, three wild pitches and a steal of home.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Cubs allowed a first inning run to the Sox, then scored three unearned runs on two Sox errors to take an early lead.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Sox tied the game in the third on George Davis' theft of home on the front end of a double steal and then took the lead for good with a four-run rally in the fourth and held on for the victory to take a 3–2 lead in the series.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] A 12-hit attack led by Frank Isbell's four doubles were enough to overcome seven unearned runs by the Cubs caused by six errors committed by the normally solid Sox defense.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] "Big" Ed Walsh earned his second win of the series, although he needed three innings of relief help from Doc White.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Isbell would remain the sole major league player to get four extra-base hits in one postseason game until Shohei Ohtani hit two doubles and two home runs in Game 3 of the 2025 World Series.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Mordecai Brown, again pitching on only one day of rest, didn't make it out of the second inning as the Hitless Wonders White Sox stunned the 116–36 Cubs in the Series finale.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The Sox battered Brown for seven runs on eight hits while getting a solid pitching performance from Doc White.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] Although the Cubs scored a run and loaded the bases in the ninth, White got Frank Schulte to ground out for the final out of the series and the White Sox won the World Series.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] The powerful Cubs went on to win the next two World Series from the Detroit Tigers, despite falling far short of 116 wins in either season, for the last Cubs win in a World Series for over a hundred years.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] This game remains the only time the Chicago White Sox have clinched a postseason series in their home ballpark.
[src:strikeout/1906-world-series] It was the only time a Chicago-based team had ever clinched a series at home until the Cubs won the 2015 National League Division Series on their home field.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] The **1929 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball for the 1929 season.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] The 26th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that pitted the American League (AL) champion Philadelphia Athletics against the National League (NL) champion Chicago Cubs.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] The Athletics defeated the Cubs in five games to win the Series.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] This was the first World Series game ever played at Wrigley Field.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Because seven of the eight regulars in the Cubs' lineup hit right-handed, Athletics manager Connie Mack started only right-handed pitchers during the series and kept all his left-handed pitchers in the bullpen, even though two of his best starters, Lefty Grove and Rube Walberg, were left-handed.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] The Athletics' Howard Ehmke, who started his major league career in 1915, had been a good starting pitcher, but by 1929, he was suffering from a sore arm.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Pitching only occasionally, he finished the regular season with a 7–2 record, a 3.29 earned run average, and 20 strikeouts in 54.2 innings.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Meanwhile, the Athletics had a big lead in the AL standings.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] In August, Mack told Ehmke that he was going to be released after the season.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Ehmke accepted the decision but said that he would like to pitch in a World Series game, having never done so before.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] In mid-September, with both league pennant races wrapped up, Mack had Ehmke leave the team and go on the road to scout the NL champion Cubs for the last few weeks of the season, telling him to be prepared to start game 1 of the World Series.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Mack kept the pitching decision a secret until the day of the game.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] The Athletics had plenty of good pitchers available, and players on both teams were surprised that Ehmke was starting.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] However, with his knowledge of the Cubs' batters and a rested arm, Ehmke pitched a complete game, winning 3–1 with no earned runs allowed and 13 strikeouts.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] The strikeout total broke the World Series record that had been set by Ed Walsh in 1906; Ehmke's record then stood until it was broken by Carl Erskine in 1953.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] This ended up being the last win of Ehmke's career and also became one of the most famous games in baseball history.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Attending the game was nine-year-old John Paul Stevens, who would grow up to become a Supreme Court Justice.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Behind the pitching of George Earnshaw and Grove, the Athletics won 9–3 and took a 2–0 lead in the series.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Jimmie Foxx became the first player to homer in his first two World Series games.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Al Simmons also homered and had four runs batted in.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Game 3 was a pitchers' duel that featured many tense moments.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Guy Bush won this game for the Cubs' only victory, holding the Athletics to one run despite allowing nine hits and two walks.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Earnshaw started his second straight game for the Athletics and allowed only one earned run himself.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Sticking to his right-handed-pitchers-only policy, Mack again made a risky move in Game 4 by starting 46-year-old Jack Quinn.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Unlike Ehmke, however, Quinn was no challenge to the Cubs' hitters, who scored seven runs off him before Mack pulled him in the sixth inning.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Trailing 8–0, the Athletics then scored 10 runs in the bottom of the seventh inning and won the game.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] In the middle of the rally that became known as the "Mack Attack", Cubs center fielder Hack Wilson lost Mule Haas's fly ball in the sun, and Haas circled the bases for a three-run inside-the-park home run, bringing the Athletics to within a run at 8–7.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] This was the last inside-the-park home run in a World Series game until Game 1 of the 2015 World Series.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] The eight-run deficit overcome by the Athletics is still the largest in postseason history.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Art Nehf's relief pitching appearance in this game was his last in the major leagues.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Mack gave Ehmke his second start of the Series, but without the advantage of surprise, he was less effective, touched for two runs, and taken out in the fourth inning.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] The Athletics trailed 2–0 going into the bottom of the ninth.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] However, Haas tied the game up with a two-run homer.
[src:strikeout/1929-world-series] Then, after a double by Simmons and an intentional walk to Foxx, Bing Miller's double scored Simmons to give the Athletics their first World Series championship in 16 years.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] The **1953 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1953 season.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] The Yankees won in six games for their fifth consecutive title—a mark which has not been equalled—and their 16th overall.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] It was also the last of seven consecutive World Series wins by teams from the American League, the longest such streak for the AL in series history.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Billy Martin was the standout player of the series as he hit .500 with a record-tying 12 hits and a walk-off RBI single in Game 6.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Before a full house (69,734 in attendance), the Yankees scored four runs in the first inning.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Brooklyn starter Carl Erskine did not last past the first.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] After a one-out walk, an RBI triple by Hank Bauer put the Yankees up 1–0.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] After a strikeout, two more walks loaded the bases before Billy Martin cleared them with a triple of his own and the Dodgers pinch-hit for Erskine in the top of the second.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] They did not score off Allie Reynolds until the fifth on a Jim Gilliam home run.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Yogi Berra matched it in the bottom of the fifth with a home run of his own, and the Yankee lead looked safe until a leadoff home run by Gil Hodges and two-run home run by pinch-hitter George Shuba chased Reynolds in the sixth.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Brooklyn tied it an inning later against Johnny Sain with consecutive leadoff singles by Roy Campanella, Hodges and Carl Furillo.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] A home run by unsung first baseman Joe Collins proved the game-winner off Clem Labine, with winning pitcher Johnny Sain providing two more runs himself in the eighth off Ben Wade with a two-run double.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Sain then scored on a Joe Collins single, and pitched a scoreless ninth to give the Yankees a 9–5 win and 1–0 series lead.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] He looked shaky in the first, walking three, hitting a batter, and allowing a sacrifice fly to Yogi Berra for the game's first run, but Brooklyn's Preacher Roe settled down after that and engaged Eddie Lopat in a complete-game pitching duel.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Billy Cox's two-run double after back-to-back two-out singles in the fourth inning put the Dodgers up 2–1.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Billy Martin's leadoff home run off Roe in the seventh inning tied the score.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] The game-winning blast came from Mickey Mantle, a two-run shot to left field in the bottom of the eighth.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Brooklyn got two runners aboard in the ninth, but Lopat was able to retire Duke Snider on a game-ending grounder to second base.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Although the Yankees won the Series, Brooklyn had at least one shining moment, as pitcher Carl Erskine set a new Series record by striking out 14 Yankees in Game 3.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] That broke Howard Ehmke's 1929 record by one.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Ersk's record would stand until Sandy Koufax got 15 in 1963.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] In that same game, Yogi Berra was hit twice by Erskine, making him the first American League player in World Series history to be a hit-batsman twice during the same game.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] The Yankees struck first in the fifth on an RBI single by Gil McDougald with runners on second and third, but the Dodgers tied it in the bottom half on Billy Cox's fielder's choice with Jackie Robinson at third.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Robinson's RBI single next inning put the Dodgers up 2–1, but again the game became tied at 2–2 in the eighth on an RBI single by the Yankees' Gene Woodling.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] The decisive blow came in the bottom of the inning when Vic Raschi surrendered a Roy Campanella home run, which proved to be the game-winner.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] The home team won for the fourth consecutive time.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Whitey Ford lasted just one inning as the Yankees' starter, allowing a leadoff ground-rule double to Jim Gilliam, who scored on Jackie Robinson's single.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] After a forceout, wild pitch and intentional walk, Duke Snider's two-run double made it 3–0 Dodgers.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Gilliam's double in the fourth off Tom Gorman made it 4–0, but Brooklyn's lead was cut in half in the fifth when Billy Loes gave up a two-run home run to Gil McDougald.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Snider's leadoff home run in the sixth off Johnny Sain made it 5–2 Dodgers, then after a double and single, Gilliam's sacrifice fly extended that lead to 6–2.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Next inning, after a two-out walk, Snider's RBI double off Art Schallock made it 7–2 Dodgers.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] In the ninth, two singles and walk loaded the bases with no outs for the Yankees.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Clem Labine relieved Loes and got two-outs before Mickey Mantle's RBI single cut the Dodgers' lead to 7–3, but Billy Martin was thrown out trying to score from second base to end the game, tying the series 2–2.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Yankees manager Casey Stengel gave the ball to Jim McDonald for Game 5 and, while he gave up a dozen hits, he got them a win.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Brooklyn starter Johnny Podres was jolted by a Gene Woodling home run to begin the game.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] After the Dodgers tied the game in the second on two singles followed by shortstop Phil Rizzuto's throwing error on Carl Furillo's ground ball, Podres was chased in a five-run third.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Rizzuto drew a leadoff walk, moved to third on two groundouts, and scored on when first baseman Gil Hodges misplayed Joe Collins's groundball.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] A hit-by-pitch and walk loaded the bases, and the first man Podres's replacement Russ Meyer faced was Mickey Mantle, who greeted him with a grand slam.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Duke Snider's RBI single after a hit-by-pitch and single made it 6–2 Yankees in the fifth, but in the seventh, Billy Martin's two-run home run off Meyer extended their lead to 8–2.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Rizzuto singled with two outs and scored on McDonald's double.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] He was relieved by Bob Kuzava, who struck out Dick Williams to end the inning.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Each team got a run in the ninth on a home run, Gil McDougald for the Yankees off Joe Black and Jim Gilliam for the Dodgers off Kuzava.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Allie Reynolds was brought in to retire Jackie Robinson for the final out.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] In Game 6, after a walk, strikeout and single, Yogi Berra's ground-rule double put the Yankees up 1–0 in the first off Carl Erskine.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] After an intentional walk loaded the bases, an error on Billy Martin's ground ball made it 2–0 Yankees.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Next inning, Gene Woodling's sacrifice fly after two leadoff singles made it 3–0 Yankees.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Starter Whitey Ford pitched five shutout innings, but in the sixth, allowed a one-out double to Jackie Robinson, who stole third and scored on Roy Campanella's groundout.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Down 3–1 in the ninth, Brooklyn rallied back on a Duke Snider walk followed by a Carl Furillo home run off Allie Reynolds.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] However, Yankee second baseman Billy Martin—who made a game-saving catch in Game 7 of the 1952 World Series—again ruined the Dodgers' dreams of a championship.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] In the bottom of the ninth, with a runner on second base, Martin drilled a Clem Labine sinker up the middle for a Series-winning RBI single.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Dropping their seventh Series without a victory, the Dodgers terminated manager Chuck Dressen's contract; Dressen was demanding two more years.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Walter Alston took his place and managed the Dodgers for the next 23 seasons (1954–1976), leading them to four World Series championships in 1955, 1959, 1963, and 1965 before being replaced by Tommy Lasorda, who would manage the team for 20 years himself (1976–1996).
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Lasorda would lead the Dodgers to a pair of World Series championships in 1981 and 1988.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] The Series was broadcast on NBC television, with Yankees announcer Mel Allen and Dodgers announcer Vin Scully describing the action; and on Mutual radio, with Al Helfer and Gene Kelly announcing.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] For the first time, it was broadcast in the cities of Canada.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] It was also seen via film recordings on CMQ in Cuba.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Red Barber, Vin Scully's senior on the Dodgers' broadcast crew, was originally selected to work with Allen on NBC, but was removed from the Series due to a salary dispute with Gillette, which sponsored the broadcasts.
[src:strikeout/1953-world-series] Scully, at the age of 25, became the youngest man to broadcast a World Series game (a record that stands to this day).
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The **1963 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1963 season.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The 60th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that matched the American League (AL) champion and two-time defending World Series champion New York Yankees against the National League (NL) champion Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The Dodgers swept the Series in four games to secure their second World’s championship in five years, and their third in franchise history.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Dodgers starting pitchers Sandy Koufax, Don Drysdale, and Johnny Podres, and ace reliever Ron Perranoski combined to give up only four runs in four games.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The dominance of the Dodgers pitchers was so complete that at no point in any of the four games did the Yankees have the lead.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] New York was held to a .171 team batting average, the lowest ever for the Yankees in the postseason.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Koufax, who pitched 2 complete games with a 1.50 ERA and 23 strikeouts, was named the World Series Most Valuable Player.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Koufax was the first player since the introduction of the award in the 1955 Series to be named league MVP and World Series MVP in the same calendar year.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Coincidentally, the 1955 World Series was also won by the Dodgers.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] This was the first time in their history that the Yankees were swept in a World Series in four straight games — the 1922 World Series had one tie.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Of the Dodgers' nine World championships to date, this remains the only one clinched in their home ballpark (although their 2020 title was won as the designated "home team" as part of that year's neutral-site World Series in Arlington, Texas).
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] This series was also the first meeting between teams from New York City and Los Angeles for a major professional sports championship.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Eight more such meetings have followed with four more times each in the World Series, three in the NBA Finals, and the 2014 Stanley Cup Final.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Despite injuries that limited Mickey Mantle to just 65 games, the Yankees went 104–57 to win their fourth straight American League pennant—this one by 10+1⁄2 games.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Catcher Elston Howard (.287 BA, 28 HRs, 85 RBI) won the MVP Award, while Joe Pepitone, Roger Maris, and Tom Tresh also topped the 20 home run mark.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Their pitching was anchored by Whitey Ford (24 wins, 2.74 ERA) and Jim Bouton (21 wins, 2.53 ERA).
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The Dodgers' road to the World Series was much more challenging.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] After blowing a four-game lead with seven to play in 1962, the Dodgers again built a lead in 1963.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] On August 21, the Dodgers beat the Cardinals 2–1 in 16 innings to take a 7+1⁄2 game lead.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Louis for a three-game series on September 16, their lead was one game over the Cardinals, who had won 19 of 20 games.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Sports fans around the country were saying how the Dodgers were going to blow it again.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] But the Dodgers swept the three games from the Cardinals to move four games ahead with nine to play; a 4–1 win over the Mets clinched the pennant in the season's 158th game.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Sandy Koufax started it off with a record 15-strikeout performance in Game 1 to outduel the Yankees' ace left-hander Whitey Ford.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The 15 strikeouts bested fellow Dodgers pitcher Carl Erskine's mark in 1953 by one, and would be surpassed by Bob Gibson in 1968 with 17.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Koufax also tied a World Series record when he fanned the first five Yankees he faced.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Clete Boyer was the only Yankees regular not to strike out.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Mickey Mantle, Tom Tresh and Tony Kubek each struck out twice, and Bobby Richardson struck out three times—his only three-strikeout game in 1448 regular season or World Series games.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Koufax also struck out three pinch-hitters, including Harry Bright to end the game.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Ford set the Dodgers down in order in the first inning, but got into trouble in the second inning.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] With one out, right fielder Frank Howard doubled into left center field.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] A single by first baseman Bill Skowron plated Howard to give the Dodgers a 1–0 lead.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Second baseman Dick Tracewski's single preceded a three-run home run by catcher John Roseboro to give the Dodgers a 4–0 lead.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The Dodgers upped the lead to 5-0 when Skowron singled home Willie Davis with two outs in the third inning against Ford, who went just five innings.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The Yankees scored twice in the eighth inning when Tony Kubek singled with one out and Tom Tresh homered with two outs to cut the lead to 5–2.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Willie Davis doubled in two runs in the first inning (after Maury Wills and Jim Gilliam singled), former Yankee Bill Skowron homered in the fourth, and Tommy Davis had two triples, including an RBI triple in the eighth after a second Davis double, to lead the Dodger offense.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Yankee starter Al Downing, who would take the loss, went only five innings and charged with three runs.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Ralph Terry, in relief, allowed Davis's RBI triple.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Dodger manager Walt Alston went with #3 starter Johnny Podres over #2 starter Don Drysdale because he was left-handed and Yankee Stadium was favorable to left-handed pitchers.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Podres delivered a six-hitter through 8+1⁄3 innings; ace reliever Ron Perranoski, also a left-hander, got the last two outs and the save, and the Dodgers headed home with 2–0 Series lead.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Yankees right fielder Roger Maris left the game in the third after hurting his left arm running into the right field foul wall while chasing down Tommy Davis's first triple and would miss the final two games of the series.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] He was replaced by Héctor López, who actually doubled and Elson Howard singled him home in the eighth for the Yankees' only run that game.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Don Drysdale pitched a masterful three-hitter at Dodger Stadium in his complete-game win.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Manager Walter Alston called Drysdale's performance "one of the greatest pitched games I ever saw." Jim Bouton, making his first World Series start, dueled Drysdale throughout, permitting only four hits in seven innings for a losing cause.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The lone run of the game came in the bottom of the first on a Jim Gilliam walk, a wild pitch and a two-out single by Tommy Davis.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Gilliam almost scored again in the eighth off Hal Reniff, but was caught in an attempt to steal third.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The final out came on Joe Pepitone's drive that backed Dodger right fielder Ron Fairly up against the bullpen gate to make the catch of a ball that would have been a home run in Yankee Stadium.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Tony Kubek had two of the Yankees' three hits, but none of the hits were extra-base hits.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Aces were on the mound again in a game 1 rematch between Whitey Ford and Sandy Koufax.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The Dodgers scored first in the bottom of the fifth on a monumental Frank Howard home run into the second (Loge) level at Dodger Stadium.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The Yankees tied it on a Mickey Mantle home run in the top of the seventh.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] But in the bottom of the inning, Gilliam hit a high hopper to Yankee third baseman Clete Boyer; Boyer leaped to make the grab, and fired an accurate throw to first base.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] But first baseman Joe Pepitone lost Boyer's peg in the white-shirted crowd background; the ball struck Pepitone in the arm and rolled down the right field line, allowing Gilliam to scamper all the way to third base.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] He then scored a moment later on Willie Davis' sacrifice fly.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] Sandy Koufax went on to hold the Yankees for the final two innings for a 2–1 victory and the Dodgers' third world championship.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] To date, this is the only time the Dodgers have won the deciding game of a World Series at home.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The World Series Most Valuable Player Award went to Sandy Koufax, who started two of the four games and had two complete game victories.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] He struck out 23 batters and only surrendered three earned runs, recording an ERA of 1.50.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] When the award was given to Koufax at a luncheon in New York City, he was presented with a new car—while the luncheon was taking place, a New York City police officer put a parking violation ticket on the car's windshield.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The Yankees' four runs in the series was, at the time, the second-lowest total in a World Series, as the Philadelphia Athletics had scored only three runs in 1905.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The Los Angeles Dodgers would set a new low in 1966, two runs.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The Yankees returned to the World Series the next year, but lost to the St.
[src:strikeout/1963-world-series] The Dodgers returned to the World Series two years later, and defeated the Minnesota Twins in seven games after trailing two-games-to-none in the series.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The **1968 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1968 season.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The 65th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff between the American League (AL) champion Detroit Tigers and the National League (NL) champion (and defending World Series champion) St.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Tigers won in seven games for their first championship since 1945, and the third in their history.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Tigers came back from a three-games-to-one deficit to win three consecutive games, largely on the arm of Mickey Lolich, who was named World Series Most Valuable Player (MVP); as of 2026, he remains the last pitcher to earn three complete-game victories in a single World Series.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] In his third appearance in the Series, Lolich had to pitch after only two days' rest in the deciding Game 7, because regular-season 31-game winner Denny McLain was moved up to Game 6 – also on two days' rest.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] In Game 5, the Tigers' hopes for the title would have been in jeopardy had Bill Freehan not tagged out Lou Brock in a home plate collision, on a perfect throw from left fielder Willie Horton, when Brock elected not to slide and went in standing up.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The 1968 season was tagged "The Year of the Pitcher", and the Series featured dominant performances from Cardinals pitcher Bob Gibson, MVP of the 1964 and 1967 World Series.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Gibson came into the World Series with a regular-season earned run average (ERA) of just 1.12, a modern era record, and he pitched complete games in Games 1, 4, and 7.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] He was the winning pitcher in Games 1 and 4.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] In Game 1, he threw a shutout, striking out a Series record 17 batters, besting Sandy Koufax's 1963 record by two; it still stands as the World Series record today.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] In Game 4, a solo home run by Jim Northrup was the only offense the Tigers were able to muster, as Gibson struck out ten batters.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] In Game 7, Gibson was defeated by series MVP Lolich, allowing three runs on four straight hits in the seventh inning, although the key play was a Northrup triple that was seemingly misplayed by center fielder Curt Flood and could have been the third out with no runs scoring.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The World Series saw the Cardinals lose a Game 7 for the first time in their history.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] This was the sixth World Series of the 1960s to go to a full seven games, the most of any decade.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Tigers were the third team to come back from a three-games-to-one deficit to win a best-of-seven World Series, the first two being the 1925 Pirates and the 1958 Yankees; since then, the 1979 Pirates, the 1985 Royals, and the 2016 Cubs have also accomplished this feat.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Detroit manager Mayo Smith received some notoriety for moving outfielder Mickey Stanley to shortstop for the 1968 World Series, which has been called one of the gutsiest coaching moves in sports history by multiple sources.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Stanley, who replaced the superior fielding but much weaker hitting Ray Oyler, would make two errors in the Series, neither of which led to a run.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Thus, it was the final World Series that guaranteed the teams with the best records from each league would be playing.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Tigers pitcher Mickey Lolich was named World Series MVP.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Lolich compiled a 3-0 record (all three of his starts were complete games), with a 1.67 ERA and 21 strikeouts.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] As of 2026, this is the last time that the Tigers clinched a World Series championship on the road.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Tigers roared into Game 1 by setting a then-team record with 103 victories on the season and were appearing in their first World Series in 23 years.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Tigers led the American League with 185 home runs, led by left fielder Willie Horton with 36 and first baseman Norm Cash and catcher Bill Freehan added 25 each.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Their team batting average was .235, fourth best in the league; the team stole only 26 bases on the year, with Dick McAuliffe leading the team with only eight.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Cardinals, on the other hand, stole 110 bases (led by Hall of Famer Lou Brock with 68), led the NL with 48 triples, and had a team batting average of .249, but hit only 73 home runs and had only two players, Orlando Cepeda and Mike Shannon with double-digit totals.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Pitching was about even as both teams set their rotations for Game 1 with solid starters and adequate relievers.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Fans overflowed Busch Stadium for Game 1 to watch the highly anticipated match-up of the Major League's top two pitchers—the Cardinals' Bob Gibson (22–9, 1.12 ERA) and the Tigers' Denny McLain (31–6, 1.96 ERA).
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Gibson was looking to become the first National League pitcher to win six World Series games while McLain was pitching in his first World Series game.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Cardinals had far more World Series experience than the Tigers with most of the Cardinal lineup (including all nine Game 1 starters) having played in a prior World Series.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Cardinals had won the World Series the year prior in 1967 and had also won in 1964.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Both pitchers were highly competitive, fast workers, sporting overpowering fastballs coupled with excellent control.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Gibson's performance in Game 1 was phenomenal.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The menacing right-handed pitcher shut out the Tigers on just five hits, and he struck out a World Series-record 17 Detroit Tigers batters.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Cardinals broke through with three in the fourth off McLain.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] After McLain walked Roger Maris and Tim McCarver, Cardinal third baseman Mike Shannon singled in Maris and went to second base when Tiger left fielder Willie Horton misplayed the ball.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Cardinal second baseman Julián Javier followed this by singling in both baserunners to make the score 3–0.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Outfielder Lou Brock added a home run in the seventh inning to complete the scoring.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Gibson finished the game in the ninth inning with his 15th, 16th, and 17th strikeouts to pass Sandy Koufax's previous record of 15, set in the 1963 World Series.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Tigers' starting pitcher Mickey Lolich earned a complete-game victory, striking out nine batters, and the Tigers tied the Series.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Tiger outfielder Willie Horton hit a home run in the second inning; Lolich also helped his own cause with a homer in the third inning off the Cardinals' starter, Nelson Briles, scoring the eventual game-winning run.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] This was the only home run that Lolich hit during his entire professional career.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Tigers broke the game open in the sixth inning when first baseman Norm Cash led off with another homer, and second baseman Dick McAuliffe later provided a two-run single.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Cardinal first baseman Orlando Cepeda gave St.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Louis a run with an RBI single in the sixth, but that was all they scored.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Al Kaline scored in the seventh inning when Jim Northrup hit into a double play, and the Tigers scored their final two runs in the ninth inning with bases-loaded walks to Don Wert and Lolich.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] In the first of three games at Detroit's Tiger Stadium, Al Kaline started the scoring with a two-run homer in the third inning, but the Cardinals came back in the fifth inning on an RBI double by center fielder Curt Flood off starter Earl Wilson.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] After Wilson put another batter on base, catcher Tim McCarver launched a three-run home run for the eventual game-winning runs off relief pitcher Pat Dobson.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Tigers cut the deficit to just one run on a home run by Dick McAuliffe.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] But Orlando Cepeda put the game out of reach in the seventh inning by smacking a three-run home run.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Cardinals' reliever Joe Hoerner entered the game in the sixth in relief of Ray Washburn (who got the win) and earned a save with three scoreless innings pitched.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Hoerner also collected a single batting in the eighth and became the first major leaguer to get a hit in the World Series after going hitless for the entire season.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Tiger manager Mayo Smith, needing another left-handed bat in the lineup, made a major change by inserting veteran Eddie Mathews at third base.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Mathews, recovering from a spinal operation that nearly ended his career, had one hit in the last game of his major league career.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] After a 35-minute rain delay, hard-hitting Hall-of-Famer Hank Greenberg threw out the first pitch.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] McLain had trouble warming up amidst the rainfall, and was throwing with less velocity from the outset.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] A 31-game winner during the regular season, he struggled for the second time in this World Series, as this one-sided pitching match-up with Bob Gibson showed.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Lou Brock led the game off with a home run, and Mike Shannon added an RBI single later in the first inning.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Two more Cardinals runs were knocked in during the third inning on Tim McCarver's triple and Mike Shannon's double.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] McLain's troubles continued, and after a walk to Julián Javier, the umpires stopped the game due to rain with two out in the third inning.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] McLain did not return when play resumed after a one-hour and 15-minute rain delay.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Bob Gibson did return after the delay, and helped his own cause by hitting a home run off Joe Sparma in the fourth inning.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Next, Brock knocked a triple and scored on a ground-out by Roger Maris.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Cardinals' final runs came in the eighth inning when Gibson walked with the bases loaded, forcing in one run, and then Lou Brock drove in three more runs with a double.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Brock was just a single short of hitting for the cycle in this game.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Tigers' only run came in the fourth inning when Jim Northrup hit a home run.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Other than that, Gibson was a nearly perfect pitcher, tossing his second complete game in this World Series while striking out ten batters.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Cards now had a commanding 3–1 series lead.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] With the World Series on the line, the Tigers used their winner of Game 2, Mickey Lolich, as their starting pitcher.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Lolich's first inning in this game was not too promising, as he allowed an RBI single by Curt Flood and a two-run home run to Orlando Cepeda.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] However, Lolich soon settled down, striking out eight Cardinal batters and allowing no more runs.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Tigers' first baseman Norm Cash began the team comeback with a sacrifice fly in the fourth inning, plating Mickey Stanley who had tripled.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] This was followed by a Willie Horton triple and Jim Northrup's RBI single, making it a 3–2 game.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] In the fifth inning, the Cardinals had a chance to go up by two runs after Lou Brock hit a one-out double.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Cardinal second baseman Julián Javier followed with a base hit to left.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Outfielder Willie Horton fielded the ball off the ground and then fired the ball towards home plate.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The throw was not cut off by Don Wert, and instead of sliding into home plate, Brock tried to bowl over Tiger catcher Bill Freehan.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] However, Freehan caught and held onto the ball while blocking the corner of the plate with his foot, and Brock was called out.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] This was the last time that the Cardinals threatened to score in the game.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Cardinals' starting pitcher Nelson Briles was taken out of the game in the seventh inning with one runner on base, and was replaced by reliever Joe Hoerner.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] After Hoerner loaded the bases, the Tigers began a game-winning rally, with Al Kaline hitting a two-run single to give his team a 4–3 lead.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Norm Cash then knocked in an insurance run with a single.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] José Feliciano's unconventional pregame version of "The Star-Spangled Banner" aroused considerable controversy, with the Tigers and NBC getting thousands of angry letters and telephone calls about the performance.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Lolich later blamed Feliciano's unusually long rendition for causing him to get cold after his warm-ups and thus give up three early runs.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Louis to win the World Series, Tiger manager Mayo Smith chose Denny McLain again as his starting pitcher, even though he had only two days' rest and had not been very successful in his two prior Series starts.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Cardinals' manager Red Schoendienst stayed with his normal three-starter rotation, selecting Ray Washburn, who had won Game 3.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The choice of McLain paid off for the Tigers, as he pitched a complete game in a 13–1 rout of the Cardinals.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Tigers went up 2–0 in the second inning on RBI hits by Willie Horton and Bill Freehan.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] In the third, the Tigers sent 15 batters to the plate and scored 10 runs off of three Cardinals pitchers.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Jim Northrup's grand slam highlighted the inning.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Al Kaline added a home run in the fifth inning.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Cardinals' lone run came off an RBI single by Julián Javier with two outs in the bottom of the ninth, but that was all they could do against McLain.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] In a fitting end to this Series (and the final game of Roger Maris' career) the two teams' hottest pitchers, Mickey Lolich and Bob Gibson, squared off in a classic duel, until an infamous hit over the head of Curt Flood.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Like McLain in Game 6, Lolich was starting on only two days' rest.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Lolich and Gibson matched zeroes for six innings, but in the top of the seventh, Gibson surrendered two-out singles to Norm Cash and Willie Horton.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Jim Northrup then hit a hard smash to deep center; Curt Flood, who won numerous Gold Glove awards in his career, misjudged it and briefly started in on the ball before turning around to go back.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The ball one-hopped the warning track, two runs scored, Northrup wound up with a triple, and Lolich had all the runs he needed.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Flood has been criticized by some who believe he would have caught the ball had his first steps been back instead of in.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Jim Northrup said, "[Flood] slipped a little, but the ball was 40 feet over his head.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] He never had a chance to catch it." However, his teammate Denny McLain claimed in his 1975 book that "Flood blew it." Orlando Cepeda, in his 1998 autobiography *Baby Bull*, asserts that Flood would have caught the ball, had he not misjudged it.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] In the October 29, 1968, issue of *The Sporting News*, both Flood and manager Red Schoendienst indicated they would have expected the normally sure-handed outfielder to catch such a ball.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] By starting in, Flood had to both reverse direction and then regain his acceleration.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] He then slipped on the wet grass before recovering his speed, and by that time the ball was well beyond him.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Bill Freehan then doubled in Northrup, and in the top of the ninth, Don Wert added an RBI single.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Cardinals got a run in the ninth on a Mike Shannon homer, but that was all as Lolich pitched his third complete game.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The final out of the series was recorded when Bill Freehan caught a pop foul from the very next batter, Tim McCarver.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Gibson struck out eight in the losing cause, giving him a record 35 strikeouts by one pitcher in a World Series, but Lolich was named as the World Series MVP.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] This is the last World Series game to date to feature complete games from both starting pitchers.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Cardinals shortstop Dal Maxvill went hitless in 22 World Series at-bats, a record.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] As of 2026, this is the last time the Tigers played in and won a Game 7.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] NBC televised the Series, with Curt Gowdy sharing the play-by-play commentary with Cardinals announcer Harry Caray (for the games in St.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Louis) and Tigers TV announcer George Kell (for the games in Detroit).
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Tony Kubek served as field reporter and in-stands interviewer.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Jim Simpson hosted pre-game coverage along with Sandy Koufax.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] NBC Radio also broadcast the games, with Pee Wee Reese splitting play-by-play with Tigers radio announcer Ernie Harwell (for the games in St.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Louis) and Cardinals announcer Jack Buck (for the games in Detroit).
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Jim Simpson came in to do play-by-play for the last two innings of Game 7 while Harwell went down to the Tigers’ clubhouse to cover the trophy presentation and conduct post-game interviews.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] This World Series was the final NBC broadcast for Reese, who was dismissed by the network early in 1969 and replaced with Kubek as the lead color commentator alongside Gowdy on *Game of the Week* telecasts.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] All seven games of NBC's TV coverage were preserved on black-and-white kinescopes by the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation, and circulate among collectors.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] Games 1 and 5 have been commercially released; these broadcasts, as well as that of Game 7, were frequently shown on CSN (Classic Sports Network) and ESPN Classic in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] This was the last World Series played before the introduction of the Major League Baseball postseason playoff format the following year, where the American and National league pennants were decided in a five-game League Championship Series (later expanded to a seven-game series in 1985).
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The postseason would then be expanded to four teams per league in 1995 (the 1981 postseason was temporarily expanded to four teams per league due to a player’s strike), five teams per league in 2012, and then six teams per league in 2022.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Tigers would return to the postseason in 1972, losing the ALCS to the eventual World Series champion Oakland Athletics in five games.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] This was the last championship won by a Detroit-based team until the Tigers won the 1984 World Series over the San Diego Padres in five games.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] During the 1970s, the City of Detroit experienced a rare and unusual slump for all four of its teams, as neither one would win a championship, let alone play in the championship round of the four major leagues.
[src:strikeout/1968-world-series] The Cardinals would return to the World Series in 1982, and defeated the Milwaukee Brewers in seven games for their ninth championship after being eleven outs away from elimination in Game 7.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] In baseball or softball, a **strikeout** (or **strike-out**) occurs when a batter accumulates three strikes during a time at bat.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] It means the batter is out, unless the third strike is not caught by the catcher and the batter reaches first base safely as a result.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] A strikeout is a statistic recorded for both pitchers and batters, and is usually denoted by the letter **K**, or sometimes by the initialism **SO**.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] A "strikeout looking"—in which the batter does not swing and the third strike is called by the umpire—may be denoted by an inverted K (i.e.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Although a strikeout suggests that the pitcher dominated the batter, the free-swinging style that generates home runs also leaves batters susceptible to striking out.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Some of the most prolific home run hitters of all time (such as Adam Dunn, Mickey Mantle, Reggie Jackson, Alex Rodriguez, and Jim Thome) were notorious for striking out often.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Notably, Jackson and Thome respectively hold the major league records for most and second most times struck out in a career.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Conversely, Tony Gwynn who is notorious for his strikeout statistics amassing only 434 strikeouts in 10,232 plate appearances over his 20-year playing career, was also noted for his lack of home runs.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] A pitched ball is ruled a *ball* by the umpire if the batter did not swing at it and, in that umpire's judgement, it does not pass through the strike zone.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Any pitch at which the batter swings unsuccessfully or, that in that umpire's judgement passes through the strike zone, is ruled a *strike*.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Each ball and strike affects the count, which is incremented for each pitched ball with the exception of a foul ball on any count with two strikes.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] That is, a third strike may only occur by the batter swinging and missing at a pitched ball, or the pitched ball being ruled a strike by the umpire with no swing by the batter.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] A pitched ball that is struck by the batter with the bat on any count, and is not a foul ball or foul tip, is *in play*.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] A batter may also strike out by bunting, even if the ball is hit into foul territory.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] The third strike is bunted foul and is not caught by a fielder.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Thus, it is possible for a batter to strike out, but still become a runner and reach base safely if the catcher is unable to catch the third strike cleanly, and he then does not either tag out the batter or force him out at first base.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] In Japan, this is called *furinige* (振り逃げ), or "swing and escape".
[src:strikeout/strikeout] In Major League Baseball, it is known as an uncaught third strike.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] When this happens, a strikeout is recorded for both the pitcher and the batter, but no out is recorded.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Because of this, a pitcher may occasionally be able to record more than three strikeouts in one inning.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] It is also possible for a strikeout to result in a fielder's choice.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] With the bases loaded and two strikes with two outs, the catcher drops the ball or catches it on the bounce.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] The batter-runner is obliged to run for first base and other base-runners are obliged to attempt to advance one base.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Should the catcher field the ball and step on home plate before the runner from third base can score, then the runner from third base is forced out.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] In baseball scorekeeping, a swinging strikeout is recorded as a K or a **K-S**.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] A strikeout looking (where the batter does not swing at a pitch that the umpire then calls strike three) is often scored with a backwards K (**ꓘ**), and sometimes as a **K-L**, **CK**, or **Kc** (the 'c' for 'called' strike).
[src:strikeout/strikeout] In terms of gameplay, swinging and looking strikeouts are exactly equivalent; the difference in notation is simply to record this aspect of the time at bat.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Official MLB records began to differentiate swinging and looking strikeouts during the 1987 season.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Despite the scorekeeping custom of using "K" for strikeout, "SO" is the official abbreviation used by Major League Baseball.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] "K" is still commonly used by fans and enthusiasts for purposes other than official record-keeping.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] One baseball ritual involves fans attaching a succession of small "K" signs to the nearest railing, one added for every strikeout notched by the home team's pitcher, following a tradition started by New York Mets fans in honor of "Dr.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] The "K" may be reversed (**ꓘ**) in cases where the batter strikes out looking, just as it would appear on a scorecard.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Virtually every televised display of a high-strikeout major league game will include a shot of a fan's strikeout display, and if the pitcher continues to strike out batters, the display may be shown following every strikeout.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] The use of "K" for a strikeout was invented by Henry Chadwick, a newspaper journalist who is widely credited as the originator of the box score and the baseball scorecard.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] As is true in much of baseball, both the box score and scorecard remain largely unchanged to this day.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Chadwick decided to use "K", the last letter in "struck", since the letter "S" was used for "sacrifice".
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Chadwick was responsible for several other scorekeeping conventions, including the use of numbers to designate player positions.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Those unaware of Chadwick's contributions have speculated that "K" was derived from the last name of 19th-century pitcher Matt Kilroy.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] If not for the evidence supporting Chadwick's earlier use of "K", this explanation would be reasonable.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Kilroy raised the prominence of the strikeout, setting an all-time single-season record of 513 strikeouts in 1886, only two years after overhand pitching was permitted.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] His record, however, is limited to its era since the pitcher's mound was only 50 feet (15 m) from the batter during that season.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] It was moved to its current distance of 60'6" in 1893.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] The modern record (1901–present) is 383 strikeouts, held by Nolan Ryan, one better than Sandy Koufax's 382.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] For 55 years, Walter Johnson held the career strikeout record, at 3,508.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] That record fell in 1982 to Nolan Ryan, who was then passed by Steve Carlton, before Ryan took the career strikeout record for good at 5,714.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Early rules stated that "three balls being struck at and missed and the last one caught, is a hand-out; if not caught is considered fair, and the striker bound to run." The modern rule has changed very little.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] The addition of the called strike came in 1858.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] In 1880, the rules were changed to specify that a third strike had to be caught on the fly.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] A later adjustment to the dropped third strike rule specified that a batter is automatically out when there are fewer than two out and a runner on first base.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] In 1887, the number of strikes for an out was changed to four, but it was promptly changed back to three the next season.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] The rule that a third strike (only) must be caught originates in the concept that a third strike is not an automatic out, but rather puts the ball in play.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] The rule was described at least as early as Johann Christoph Friedrich GutsMuths' 1793 book *Gymnastik für die Jugend* (Gymnastics for Youth) and has remained in effect since.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] After the third strike, the ball being in play, the batter (now a runner) must be put out.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] A swinging strikeout is often called a *whiff*, while a batter who is struck out by a fastball is often said to have been *blown away*.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] A batter who strikes out on a swung third strike is said to have *fanned* (as in a fanning motion), whereas if he takes a called third strike it is called a *punch out* (describing the plate umpire's dramatic punching motion on a called third strike).
[src:strikeout/strikeout] However, sometimes these words are used as general synonyms for a strikeout, irrespective of whether it was swinging or looking.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] The announcer Ernie Harwell called a batter who took a called third strike, usually on the other team, "out for excessive window-shopping" or having "stood like the house by the side of the road".
[src:strikeout/strikeout] On a called third strike, it is said that the batter was *caught looking*, or that he looked at a strike.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Typically, a called third strike can be somewhat more embarrassing for a batter, as it shows that he was either fooled by the pitcher or, even worse, had a moment of hesitation.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] For example, Carlos Beltrán was caught looking at strike 3 to end the 2006 NLCS, and the season, for the New York Mets.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Sports commentators have also been known to refer to it as *browsing* if the batter did not move his bat at all.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] A pitcher is said to *striking out the side* when he retires all three batters in a half-inning by striking them out.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] This term is also used when all three outs were caused by strikeouts, regardless of how other batters in the inning fared.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] If a pitcher strikes out three batters on nine pitches, he is said to have pitched an *immaculate inning*.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] A batter that takes the third strike looking, especially on a breaking pitch like a slider or a curveball that appears to be out of the strike zone but drops in before he can get the bat off his shoulders, can be said to have been *frozen*.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] In slang, when a batter strikes out three times in a game, he is said to have completed a *hat trick*.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] If he strikes out four times, it is called a *golden sombrero*.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] He receives a *platinum sombrero* if he strikes out five times, and this dishonor is also known as the *Olympic rings*.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Striking out six times is a rare occurrence, which in the history of major league play has only occurred in games that went to extra innings, with Sam Horn of the Baltimore Orioles being one of the few to do this.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] The slugger's then-teammate, pitcher Mike Flanagan, told reporters after that 1991 event that six strikeouts would thereafter be known as a *Horn*.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] He added that if anyone ever strikes out seven times in one game, it will be a *Horn of Plenty*.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Some pitchers who specialize in strikeouts have acquired nicknames including the letter "K".
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Dwight Gooden was known as "Doctor K" (alluding to basketball star Julius Erving a.k.a.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Francisco Rodríguez is known as "K-Rod".
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Roger Clemens has taken the "K" name to an extreme by naming his four sons Koby, Kory, Kacy, and Kody.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Tim Lincecum is nicknamed "The Say 'K' Kid", alluding to former Giants player Willie Mays who was called "The Say Hey Kid".
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Daisuke Matsuzaka is known as "Dice-K", a term that was used as a pronunciation guide for his name when he first arrived in MLB.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Hall of Fame strikeout artist Sandy Koufax of the Los Angeles Dodgers coincidentally has a last name starting with "K", and in his call of the pitcher's perfect game in 1965, Dodgers announcer Vin Scully commented that Koufax's name "will always remind you of strikeouts".
[src:strikeout/strikeout] If a third strike is not caught cleanly by the catcher, it is still recorded as a strikeout for both the pitcher and the batter, but the batter becomes a runner and the play is still alive.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] (This is not true when first base is occupied and there are fewer than two outs; see Uncaught third strike.) The runner may take first base unless the defense tags or throws him out.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Therefore, a pitcher can achieve more than three strikeouts in one standard half-inning.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Prior to 1960, the event occurred only seven times.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] The first Major League player to be credited with the feat was Ed "Cannonball" Crane of the New York Giants on October 4, 1888.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] It has occurred in Major League Baseball 76 times.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Chuck Finley accomplished the feat on May 12 and August 15, 1999, with the Anaheim Angels and again on April 16, 2000, with the Cleveland Indians.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Pete Richert of the Los Angeles Dodgers is the only pitcher to do it in his MLB debut (April 12, 1962, against the Cincinnati Reds).
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Steve Delabar struck out four men in the 10th inning, and recorded the win in a 3–2 victory over the Chicago White Sox on August 13, 2012, making him the first pitcher in major league history to record four strikeouts in an extra inning.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] For a list of pitchers who have achieved more than three strikeouts in an inning, including the most recent pitcher to do so, see List of Major League Baseball single-inning strikeout leaders.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Five strikeouts in one inning have never occurred in a regulation Major League Baseball game.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] They have occurred at least six times at the minor league level.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] John Perkovitsh of Wisconsin Rapids did so against Oshkosh in a Wisconsin State League game on May 17, 1946, while Ron Necciai of Bristol in the Appalachian League accomplished the feat against Johnson City on May 17, 1952.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Kelly Wunsch of the Beloit Brewers fanned five in the third inning on April 15, 1994.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Mike Schultz of the Lancaster JetHawks struck out five batters in one inning on July 16, 2004, and Garrett Bauer of the Rockford RiverHawks struck out five batters in one inning on July 1, 2008.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Most recently, Malcolm Van Buren of the Burlington Royals struck out five in the seventh inning of a game on July 31, 2019.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] 2. that with fewer than two outs, the first baserunner, who reached base on an uncaught third strike, must have scored or be on a base other than first before another strikeout with a dropped 3rd strike can occur.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Alternately, one or two normal strikeouts must be recorded before the second runner can possibly reach first base on a dropped 3rd strike; only when the second batter-runner reaches base can the 5th strikeout be completed.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Houston Astros pitcher Joe Niekro struck out five Minnesota Twins batters in the first inning of an exhibition spring training game on April 7, 1976, in New Orleans.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Niekro's catcher, Cliff Johnson, was charged with five passed balls in the inning.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Exhibition games are not recorded in official statistics.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] Note: Tom Cheney struck out 21 batters overall, in a 16-inning game, September 12, 1962.
[src:strikeout/strikeout] He had 13 strikeouts through the first nine innings.
